            # so the two compilers agree on accept/reject (locked by the type-parity
            # lane). String concat/compare and structural == already returned above.
            # Conditions stay INLINE -- tychoc0 mistypes a `:=` local bound to a bool
            # from a string compare. A newtype resolves to its base for the orderable/
            # numeric tests; and/or/bitwise require the literal bool/int type (tychoc).
            # Operand validity splits into BASE-validity (on the resolved base type)
            # and newtype IDENTITY (the unresolved skin): mixing two newtypes, or a
            # newtype with its base, is rejected even though the bases match -- the
            # parity gap tychoc catches and the C compiler can't (the emitted C has
            # the base type). For non-newtype operands sl==sr=="" and rlt==lt, so every
            # original condition holds unchanged. Literal adaptation is base-only.
            rlt := resolve_nt(dc, ctx, lt)
            frlt := resolve_nt(dc, ctx, frt)
            sl := nt_skin_of(l, names, types, dc, ctx)
            sr := nt_skin_of(r, names, types, dc, ctx)
            # numeric-literal width adaptation, shared by ==/!=, ordering, AND
            # arithmetic so the three can never drift apart (they did: == and
            # ordering once omitted the f32/uint literal clauses this centralizes).
            # An int literal takes a u32/u64/f32 sibling, a float literal takes an
            # f32 sibling (non-newtype only). Mirrors tychoc's pre-adaptation
            # (src/tychoc.c ~4374), which applies uniformly to every binary op.
            lnum := is_int_lit(l) or is_float_lit(l)
            rnum := is_int_lit(r) or is_float_lit(r)
            num_lit_ok := (sl == "" and sr == "") and ((rlt == frlt and (rlt == "u32" or rlt == "u64" or rlt == "f32")) or ((rlt == "u32" or rlt == "u64") and frlt == "int" and is_int_lit(r)) or ((frlt == "u32" or frlt == "u64") and rlt == "int" and is_int_lit(l)) or (rlt == "f32" and frlt != "" and rnum) or (frlt == "f32" and rlt != "" and lnum))
